Commands that modify address book state do not commit. This prevents the address book from keeping track of changes in state.

Let's,

The application cannot run undo/redo commands because the parser does not recognize the commands.

Update DG model class diagram to include the new VersionedAddressBook

Phone, Email, and Address are optional fields in Person, represented as null if the Person does not have that field.

Let's wrap the fields in Optional, e.g. from Phone to Optional<Phone>. If the Person does not have that field, it is stored as Optional#empty().

This makes it clearer which fields in Person are optional, and enforces that the absence of the field is handled in relevant methods.

Let's abstract the repeated parsing of optional fields into its own method.

This reduces repeated code and makes it easier to understand.

The application lacks functionality to edit existing vendors.

Let's add VendorEditCommand with the relevant tests. Note that it is not hooked into the application yet.

Add VendorEditCommandParser with the relevant tests.

This allows the application to parse `vendor edit` commands.

The application cannot perform `vendor edit` commands because the parser does not recognize the command.

Let's modify VendorCommandParser to accept the command.

TableNumber is an optional field in Person, represented as null if the Person does not have that field.

Let's wrap the field in Optional. If the Person does not have a table number, it is stored as Optional#empty().

This makes it clearer which fields in Person are optional, and enforces that the absence of the field is handled in relevant methods.

Let's
* Update the command description to be clearer
* Update the UG description to match the change

commitResults.messageTitle: Model: Update predicates to be more general
commitResults.messageBody:
Some of the predicates such as GuestNamePredicate apply to any Person, hence it should not be implementing Predicate<Guest> but Predicate<Person> instead. This results in duplicated code, such as between GuestNamePredicate and VendorNamePredicate.

Unifying the duplicated code improves the code quality, and reduces the number of tests we have to write.

Let's refactor common person predicate classes into their own classes that implement Predicate<Person>, and remove the former common predicate classes.

Equality between FilterCommand is problematic as the predicates they are derived from are chained.

Let's modify predicates to be a list within FilterCommand, and delay the creation of a chained predicate from the Parser class to within the FilterCommand class itself.

This allows us to use equality of FilterCommand objects within our tests.

commitResults.messageBody:
Name is case sensitive, which means that two names like `John` and `john` are considered different names.

This is inconsistent with other sections of the code base, such as the `GuestFilterCommand` which is case-insensitive. It is also unintuitive.

Let's update the equality of name to be case insensitive.

This will also update the functionality of Person#isSamePerson, preventing users from adding two users with full names that only differ in cases.
